<TITLE> Merkel would discuss IMF aid for Greece in emergency </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BERLIN, 22 march (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Chancellor Angela Merkel would consider IMF financial aid for debt-stricken Greece in an emergency, a German government spokesman said on Monday. Spokesman Ulrich Wilhelm added, however, that Greek Prime Minister George Papandreou made clear in a telephone call with Merkel on Sunday that Greece did not need aid. Government leaders would act if the stability of the euro area is threatened, Wilhelm said. "In the case of such an emergency arising ... the financial assistance of the IMF is, for the chancellor and the government, definitely a point for discussion," Wilhelm told a regular government news conference. But he expected no decisions on aid at a summit of European leaders on Thursday and Friday. "According to the information so far, decisions on aid for Greece are not on the agenda," Wilhelm said. The president of the European Commission challenged Merkel to rise above domestic politics and agree on a financial safety net for Greece to help preserve European monetary union.Jose Manuel Barroso told a German newspaper that European Union leaders must decide at this week's summit on a support mechanism for Greece or risk harm to their common currency, noting the euro's stability was in Germany's inter
